RIDOC’s Covid-19 update
04/16/2020

Today’s Community stats:

...

Today’s stats demonstrate that we are not yet at the top of the curve. There were unfortunately 18 more deaths related to Covid-19 illness in RI, bringing our total to 105.
There are 309 new cases of Covid-19 in RI, bringing our state’s total to 3838.
There are currently 245 people in the hospital in RI with Covid-19 related illness.

RIDOC Transparency report:

As of today, there are five RIDOC staff who have tested positive for COVID19. The count of inmates with COVID19 continues to be zero.

RIDOC Message:

These are challenging times. Many people are nervous, facing uncertainty and don’t know where to turn for guidance. Many family and friends of those housed within our secured facilities are worried about the safety of their loved ones.

We hear you and understand your concerns.

Our medical and security staff are literally working around the clock to make sure our facilities are safe and secure for both staff and inmates. We are taking responsible measures to ensure the safety of everyone. RIDOC strictly complies with the Department of Health and CDC safety guidelines to help contain any spread of COVID-19, particularly in units where staff have tested positive.

Some have asked us “to let ALL the inmates out”, “why can’t we just release EVERY inmate during this pandemic for THEIR safety?”. While there are numerous ways to respond to such uninformed requests, not the least of which is how it completely and dangerously ignores community safety, the most important – the most crucial – point to understand is this: RIDOC does not have the legal authority to simply release inmates, only the courts do. This agency is responsible for custody, not sentencing. Only the Courts can order the release of inmates and affect sentencing.

You should also know that we have worked closely with the Courts, Public Defender’s office and the Attorney General’s office, to safely and responsibly reduce our census. This wide-ranging inter agency collaboration is producing measurable results. As of today, our total population is at just 57.4% capacity. It is the lowest it has been in thirty years.

Additionally, besides the early releases requested by the Public Defender’s office, inmates are being released everyday based on end of sentence.

We are very vigilant of our health practices and protocols, and while some may find these new safety measures an inconvenience, the positive results speak for themselves. These measures are keeping people safe. This is about saving human lives, and to that end, we will follow every safety measure available to us.

Please rely on vetted information from official sources, not on misinformed opinions. I hope this was helpful. Please continue to check this page for updates.

Thank you and be safe.
